info.name: dbt Cloud Object Management API Endpoints
info.description:
### Introduction

This collection contains a set of endpoints that can be used for managing resources in dbt Cloud. The endpoints documented here can be used to address use cases such as:

*   Creating, triggering, and monitoring dbt Cloud jobs
*   Migrating dbt Cloud resources (projects, environments, jobs, etc.) among dbt Cloud accounts.
*   Managing user and group permissions
    

### Obtaining your dbt Cloud API Key

The dbt Cloud API uses tokens to authenticate requests, and supports two different types of tokens:

*   User Tokens
    *   Enable the same permissions associated with your user license in the UI
    *   Retrieve from your User Profile (top right icon) > API Access
*   Service Tokens
    *   Enable permissions based on [enterprise permission sets](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/dbt-cloud/access-control/enterprise-permissions).
    *   Retrieve from Account Settings > Service Tokens > Create Service Token

Tokens obtained using either of the methods above are used in the Authentication header of requests sent to the dbt Cloud API.

### Base URL for Multi and Single-Tenant Deployments

If your dbt Cloud account is deployed on our multi-tenant infrastructure, the base URL for the API will look like `https://cloud.getdbt.com`

Single Tenant base URLs look a bit different, for example: `https://[environment].[customer].getdbt.com`

If you have questions about the base URL to use for your deployment, reach out to [support@getdbt.com](mailto:support@getdbt.com)

request.description: Note: the `dbt_project_subdirectory` is an optional field which allows you to point dbt Cloud to a subdirectory that lives within the root folder of your target repository. This means dbt Cloud will look for a `dbt_project.yml` file at that location.

Note: To set up a snowflake connection with Oauth, follow the instructions [here](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/dbt-cloud/dbt-cloud-enterprise/setting-up-enterprise-snowflake-oauth) and then set:

*   `allow_sso` to true
*   Add the `oauth_client_id` and `oauth_client_secret` variables from snowflake to your request.

Note: Environment variables must be prefixed with `DBT_` or `DBT_ENV_SECRET_` . You can read more in the [docs](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/dbt-cloud/using-dbt-cloud/cloud-environment-variables)
Note: Environment variables must be prefixed with `DBT_` or `DBT_ENV_SECRET_` . You can read more in the [docs](https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/dbt-cloud/using-dbt-cloud/cloud-environment-variables)

Note: The `group_name` is the name of the dbt Cloud group. The list of `sso_mapping_groups` are string values that dbt Cloud will attempt to match with incoming information from your identity provider at login time, in order to assign the group with `group_name` to the user.
Note: Setting the `desired_group_ids` in this request will overwrite a user's existing group assignments.
